<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="kubernetes">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Kubernetes production readiness: resource requests/limits, all three health probes, full security context hardening, PodDisruptionBudget, and HPA/VPA/Karpenter autoscaling.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>kubernetes</tag>
      <tag>k8s</tag>
      <tag>container-orchestration</tag>
      <tag>production-readiness</tag>
      <tag>security-context</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>infrastructure</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Kubernetes</title>
    <summary>Kubernetes production readiness requires: always set resource requests AND limits, configure liveness + readiness + startup probes, enforce runAsNonRoot: true + readOnlyRootFilesystem: true + allowPrivilegeEscalation: false + capabilities.drop: ["ALL"] on every container, and define a PodDisruptionBudget for every Deployment with more than one replica. Never use latest image tags in production.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>99.94% of clusters are over-provisioned (average CPU at 10%, memory at 23%) because teams skip resource requests. Without requests, the scheduler cannot make correct placement decisions, leading to node resource contention and OOMKilled events. Without security context hardening, a container escape escalates directly to cluster-admin. PDBs prevent maintenance windows from killing all replicas simultaneously.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Deploying any containerized workload that needs horizontal scaling, rolling updates, or self-healing</item>
        <item>Multi-service application where service discovery via DNS is needed</item>
        <item>Workloads requiring persistent storage with automated provisioning</item>
        <item>Environments where GitOps (ArgoCD/Flux) manages the desired state</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-container application with no scaling needs — Docker Compose or a simple VM is simpler</item>
        <item>Stateful workloads with complex data replication not supported by a Kubernetes Operator — managed databases are a better fit</item>
        <item>Batch/ETL workload that runs infrequently — serverless (Cloud Run, Lambda) avoids paying for idle nodes</item>
        <item>Team has no Kubernetes operational experience and production SLO is tight — operational learning curve is high</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="Resource Requests and Limits">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always set resource requests AND limits on every container; base requests on P95 observed usage, not guesses.</statement>
        <rationale>Without requests, the scheduler cannot make correct node placement decisions. Without limits, a runaway process can consume all node memory and evict neighboring pods. Requests set to P95 usage prevent 99.94% over-provisioning seen in typical clusters.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
resources:
  requests:
    memory: "256Mi"
    cpu: "250m"
  limits:
    memory: "512Mi"
    cpu: "500m"  # consider omitting CPU limit to avoid throttling
]]></code>
        <note>CPU limits cause throttling even when node capacity is available. Many teams omit CPU limits and rely on requests for scheduling. Memory limits remain critical — OOMKill is a hard boundary.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Setting requests equal to limits (Guaranteed QoS) for all pods.</description>
        <reason>Guaranteed QoS is appropriate for latency-sensitive workloads. For most workloads, Burstable QoS (requests lower than limits) allows better bin-packing and handles traffic spikes without OOMKill.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="Health Probes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Configure all three probes: startupProbe for slow-starting apps, readinessProbe to gate traffic, livenessProbe to restart deadlocked containers.</statement>
        <rationale>Without startupProbe, livenessProbe can kill a container during initialization before it is ready. Without readinessProbe, load balancers send traffic to pods that are not yet serving. Without livenessProbe, deadlocked processes accumulate.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
startupProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /healthz
    port: 8080
  failureThreshold: 30  # up to 5 minutes to start
  periodSeconds: 10
readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /ready
    port: 8080
  initialDelaySeconds: 5
  periodSeconds: 5
  failureThreshold: 3
livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /healthz
    port: 8080
  initialDelaySeconds: 30
  periodSeconds: 15
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="Security Context">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every container must have all four security context fields set: runAsNonRoot: true, readOnlyRootFilesystem: true, allowPrivilegeEscalation: false, capabilities.drop: ["ALL"].</statement>
        <rationale>These four together prevent the most common container escape paths. runAsNonRoot prevents trivial UID 0 exploitation. readOnlyRootFilesystem prevents persistence. drop ALL capabilities removes Linux kernel attack surface. allowPrivilegeEscalation: false prevents setuid escalation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
securityContext:
  runAsNonRoot: true
  runAsUser: 1000
  readOnlyRootFilesystem: true
  allowPrivilegeEscalation: false
  capabilities:
    drop: ["ALL"]
  seccompProfile:
    type: RuntimeDefault
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="High Availability and Disruption">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define a PodDisruptionBudget for every Deployment with more than one replica; set minAvailable to at least 1 (or maxUnavailable to 1 for larger deployments).</statement>
        <rationale>Without a PDB, a node drain during maintenance can remove all replicas simultaneously, causing a complete outage. PDB ensures at least one replica stays healthy during voluntary disruptions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never use latest as image tag in production; pin to a specific immutable tag (digest or version).</statement>
        <rationale>latest is mutable — the image it points to can change between pod restarts. A node restart can pull a different image version than the currently running pods, causing split-brain versions in a Deployment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/deployment-secure.yaml">Production Deployment with full security context, probes, PDB</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="Autoscaling">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use HPA for request-based workloads, VPA for right-sizing resource requests, Karpenter (or Cluster Autoscaler) for node-level scaling — they complement each other.</statement>
        <rationale>HPA adds/removes pods based on load. VPA adjusts the resources per pod based on observed usage. Karpenter provisions/deprovisioned nodes based on pending pods. All three are needed for fully elastic clusters.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: my-app
  minReplicas: 2
  maxReplicas: 20
  metrics:
    - type: Resource
      resource:
        name: cpu
        target:
          type: Utilization
          averageUtilization: 70
    - type: Resource
      resource:
        name: memory
        target:
          type: AverageValue
          averageValue: 400Mi
]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Setting HPA minReplicas to 1 for production services.</description>
        <reason>A single replica has no redundancy during rolling updates, node maintenance, or pod restarts. Use minReplicas: 2 minimum; add PodAntiAffinity to spread across nodes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="Deployment Strategies">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Rolling Update (default) for most deployments; use Argo Rollouts for canary or blue-green when needing traffic control and automatic rollback based on metrics.</statement>
        <rationale>Native blue-green requires two full Deployments and manual Service switching. Argo Rollouts automates traffic splitting, analysis, and rollback based on error rate thresholds — reducing human error during production deploys.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Rolling Update: gradual pod replacement, zero downtime, simple — default for most</item>
        <item>Blue/Green: instant traffic switch, full environment switch, instant rollback — use for breaking changes</item>
        <item>Canary (Argo Rollouts): % traffic split, metric-based promotion, automatic rollback — use for high-risk changes</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="Observability">
      <rule>
        <statement>Instrument every service with RED metrics (Rate, Error rate, Duration) and expose them on /metrics for Prometheus scraping.</statement>
        <rationale>RED metrics answer the three most important production questions: how much traffic, how many errors, how slow. Without them, diagnosis requires log parsing which is slower and less precise.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Rate: requests/second — detect traffic spikes and drops</item>
        <item>Errors: 5xx/4xx per second — detect regressions immediately after deploy</item>
        <item>Duration: P50/P95/P99 latency — detect performance degradation before users complain</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define SLO-based alerts on error budget burn rate rather than raw threshold alerts on individual metrics.</statement>
        <rationale>A 1% error rate at 1000 RPS means 10 errors/s — critical. At 1 RPS it means 0.01 errors/s — negligible. Burn rate alerts scale with traffic and prevent alert fatigue.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/hpa.yaml">HPA with CPU and custom metric targets</reference>
      <reference path="templates/networkpolicy-default-deny.yaml">Default-deny NetworkPolicy with explicit ingress/egress</reference>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/deployment-secure.yaml" purpose="Production Deployment with full security context, probes, resources, PDB"/>
      <template path="templates/hpa.yaml" purpose="HPA with CPU + custom metric targets"/>
      <template path="templates/networkpolicy-default-deny.yaml" purpose="Default-deny NetworkPolicy with explicit ingress/egress"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-review.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for reviewing a Kubernetes manifest for production readiness"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
